title.narrative: OUTPUT 2.2: MICRONUTRIENT DEFICIENCIES

description.narrative: Output 2.2: Micronutrient deficiencies prevented in food insecure and deprived communities targeting highly vulnerable children and women through full EPHS implementation of 90% of health facilities, which contributes to Infant And Young Child Feeding, Micronutrients, Prevention Of Stunting And Other Forms Of Malnutrition. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Public Engagement, Evaluations, Research And Data, Operational Support To Programme Delivery, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: Outcome 2: By 2019, the nutritional status of children under five years, adolescent girls, and women of child bearing age improved with special focus on the reduction of chronic malnutrition in children below2 years.

description.narrative: As at October 2019, 190,298 children aged 6–23 months had received MNP supplementation. This translates to 81% coverage against an annual coverage target of 73%, indicating significant achievement. About 130,050 pregnant women received IFA supplementation (60% against an annual target of 91%), with the slow progress due to stockouts of supplies. The first round of the Vitamin A supplementation campaign reached 622,799 children aged 6–59 months. | Status:Met | As-of Date:26/12/2019
